The paper deals with motion planning, which is a subfield of robotics (cs.RO). The use of probabilistic models and machine learning techniques to estimate the belief of collision-free configurations suggests that the paper could also belong to the subfields of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also mentions the use of distance metrics and weighting matrices, which are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV). Finally, the paper's focus on computational efficiency and optimization suggests that it could also belong to the subfield of control systems (cs.SY).
